@Node WHY "Exactly WHY you should Register Wheel of Fortune?"

    I'm not one who agrees with the idea of releasing only HALF a project,
or crippling certain features of a project in the HOPE of making money.

    However, I am one who follows the addage "Be nice to me, and I'll be
REAL nice to you!", which is what I intend to do for all REGISTERED SysOps
of The Wheel of Fortune, v6.41!

    Although you've received everything you need to fully use this software
package, I have made available certain "extras" for those who really like
this game and wish to use it to it's fullest extent.
@endnode
@Node WHERE "Where to send your Registration"

    To register this game, send $15.00 to the following address:

                    David M. Weeks
                    318 Woodside Avenue
                    Buffalo, NY 14220-2015

                    ATTN: Dotoran

    Please include the ATTN, as I have this tendancy to simply toss all my
mail in a pile, until I'm ready to deal with it(Bills, mostly). This will
immediately notify me it has something to do with the BBS, and should be
acted upon as soon as possible.

****** PLEASE READ BELOW ******

    You must also call my Bulletin Board, Frontiers BBS, to establish an
account, as that is how I will be releasing Key Files, Registered Files,
and other materials. Once I have received your registration fee, you will
be given access to the "Reg. WOF v6.x Files" base inside my CNet SysOps UD
Base. Your Key file will be sent to you via File-Mail on Frontiers BBS.

****** PLEASE READ ABOVE ******
@endnode
@Node H2H "The Head-to-Head Module Allowing Multiple Players!"

    The third beta-release of the H2H module has already been made as of
this writing. The game is complete with 3-Player games, single player
games, two-player games, and the ability to choose what your contestant
will look like! Full chatting ability has been integrated, as well as the
ability for an infinite number of users to WATCH a game. WATCHERS of a game
may also chat with the PLAYERS of the game, so it's kind of similar to
CONFERENCE in that affect. I'm still playing around with noises, computer
opponents, etc, so there WILL be future releases coming soon!

    Further work on the H2H module(s) has been temporarily suspended until
after I've had a chance to see what the new CNET version looks like. I
anticipate MANY internal changes in this upcoming version that will have
a drastic effect on pre-existing pfiles, so my work may be cut out for me
for quite a deal of time.
@endnode
@Node WHAT "So, what DO you get for your Registration right Now?"

So, what WILL you be getting NOW for your $15.00?

   - Over 2000 Additional Puzzles, on top of the original 350, PLUS any
     others I happen to accumulate between now and the time you register,
     which should make this at least 2500 or more Puzzles!

   - You will receive at LEAST five(5) utilities written in ANSI-ARexx,
     similarly to the way the "Config" Module is written.  Here are the
     descriptions for the utilities as they stand now:

           - The "GamEditor" (Game Editor) [Already Completed]

                   - Allows for editing of ANY DATA found in these
                     game support files:

                     GameData, Players, Stats, Winner, BWinner
                     Winners, BWinners, Millionaires, BMillioanires,
                     Bankers, LastPlayer and LastReset files!

           - The "PuzEditor" (Puzzle Editor) [Already Completed]

                   - Allows you to do MANY various edit operations to
                     the "PuzData" file, including:

                       - Edit Puzzles, Clues, and Authors.
                       - Move anywhere within the "PuzData" file.
                       - Mark Puzzles for deletion, copying, etc.
                       - Mark Puzzles by same Author and/or Clue.
                       - Kill all Marked Puzzles.
                       - Swap two or more Puzzle locations.
                       - Add NEW Puzzles manually.
                       - Add NEW Puzzles using the "NewPuz" file.
                       - Add NEW Puzzles using some other file.
                       - Pull(Copy) Puzzle to a text file.
                       - Pull Marked Puzzles to a text file.
                       - Create a text backup of the "PuzData" file.
                       - Restore(ReCreate) the "PuzData" from Backup.
                       - Create sorted text list by PUZZLE TITLE.
                       - Create sorted text list by PUZZLE CLUE.
                       - Create sorted text list by PUZZLE AUTHOR.
                       - Shuffle the "PuzData" file w/o Resetting Game.

           - The "RegEditor" (Reg Graphic Editor) [Already Completed]

                   - Will allow you to specify the colors used when
                     displaying one of the newly defined Registered
                     Graphic Screens. You now have the ability to use
                     different colors for the ANSI and IBM-ANSI screens.

                   - You should run this utility every time you upgrade
                     your WOF package, as the VERSION number will be
                     read in from the "WoFortune.Config" file.

           - The "ColEditor" (Color Editor) [Already Completed]

                   - This utility will allow you to change the color
                     scheme(s) used within the "Game.ANS" and "Game.IBM"
                     Game Modules, which means you can now have the
                     game use your own favorite color scheme(s).

           - The "HisEditor" (History Editor) [Already Completed]

                   - This utility allows you to edit any player's User
                     Config file settings, as well as any of the prizes
                     contained in their WOF Prize History.

   - You will also receive some text files that will be of use to any
     interested ARexx Programmers. These files explain a bit how each
     support file is set up, and if time avails itself to me, I may
     include a short doc file explaining some of the routines used in
     the game, which may prove useful for anybody interested in trying
     their own hand at programming in ARexx for CNet Amiga.

   - Lastly, you'll be able to create three NEW "Reg." Graphic Screens
     that I believe to be a bit nicer to look at. You will also be
     issued a new key file, using a new filename, which makes your
     "WOF.Key" file obsolete.
@endnode
@Node HOW "How can you go about making the `Registration' decision?"

    To further aid you in making the "Register" decision, I've included a
directory within the "pfiles:WoFortune/" directory that contains ANSI
Screen shots of the utilities already completed. This will give you an
idea of what you COULD be using, if you only Registered. Note the inclusion
of the CONFIG screens, as initially, I was only going to include this for
REGISTERED SysOps only, but decided against it to show you this kind of
utility DOES exist, and is NOT a scam to get your money. If you'd like a
guided tour of ANY of the completed Registered Utilities, simply call my
board and see if I'm around, as I'd be more than willing to let you play
with them online(as they were written to be usable from REMOTE equally well
as from LOCAL mode!)

    Well, it is my hope that these paragraphs were enough to make you want
to pursue the "Registered" status as quickly as possible. Please check with
your users, because if they enjoy playing the game, they may not mind
giving you some, or all of the money needed to cover this LOW registration
fee:

        15 users @ $1.00 apiece...
        30 users @ $0.50 apiece...
        60 users @ $0.25 apiece...

    Not very much money, when you consider the time, effort, and QUALITY of
this game!
                                                Think About It!

                                                            Dotoran
@endnode
@Node DOTORAN "Everything you always wanted to know about Dotoran!"

 The History of Dotoran
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    I started running boards on a Commodore 128 computer. I actually was
going to buy a Commodore 64 to run CNet 64, but then I began seeing the
ads for the new 128 version of CNet. I decided to purchase the 128 and
wait the 2-3 mos. that it would take to get the 128 version. As it ended
up, I was the 53rd person to own a copy of CNet 128, with a serial number
of 0053, v1.01e was what was shipped to me. This version was written
mainly in BASIC, with some ML routines for the heavier maintenance
routines. The base of the program was a large BASIC program, which also
contained the majority of the text the program used. I wrote my first
program for the 128 version more than 7 years ago: January 12, 1988. I
went on to write mods, text files, gfiles and MANY, MANY pfiles for CNet
128, including Murder Motel, Seventh Seas, Hangman, Jotto, Utopia(similar
to Empire), as well as numerous single player games. Overall, I wrote
somewhere around 50 different files for that version before deciding to
take the Amiga Plunge.

    It took almost a year to get my first Amiga BBS up and running, but
once it did firm-up, it's existed at the same number for the past three
years. My first CNet Amiga version running was v2.16e, however I started
writing stuff for it under my old 128 pseudonym of The Marshal during the
v1.0 days. A close friend of mine ran a board using the newest Amiga CNet
software, which is how I obtained my first xeroxed copies of MCI codes and
ARexx commands. It took about 4 months to learn the basics of ARexx, which
really weren't much harder than the BASIC coding I had been using for the
128 versions.

    My first pfile for CNet Amiga was a number guesser file, but my 2nd
file was nowhere near as easy. Wordo was the name of that second program-
ming effort. It took quite some time to get all the bugs worked out of
that one, but it was one HUGE learning experience. That was also the first
file to use ANSI coding, as well as MCI's. I guess you could say it was
the file that initially molded my style of programming.

    Having been self-taught, I obtained the majority of my knowledge
reading other's code, even using it if I couldn't figure it out for myself.
Something that I thought was VERY lacking in the AMIGA CNET world were the
HELPFUL text files, users, SysOps, etc. which is what got me going on my
"HELP" crusade, which produced such efforts as the GETUSER packages,
BBSTEXT HELP package, CNet ToolKits, CNet-Specific ARexx Command Listings,
CNet-JamMail packages, etc. as I wanted to know this information, but
because noone else felt like sharing the knowledge I placed it on myself
to make sure I had the most up-to-date knowledge and that OTHERS were FREE
to have this knowledge as well.

    Lately, things have slowed down a bit, mainly due to the fact I'm back
to work again(there was a 1 and a half year spell where I wasn't working
where things were really being cranked out at this end), but I do still
find time to release something new now and again. For my larger efforts,
I'd have to say I'm proudest of my Wheel of Fortune game, BBS-Stats file,
Call-Logger, View-Log, CNet Pager, LogActs File and the new SuperTags
file. From my text file efforts, I'd have to say the GETUSER package was
the most beneficial, however I see this falling flat on it's face come the
arrival of the next new CNet Amiga version, but then again, there'll be my
NEXT challenge!
@endnode
